&gt; I would agree. I spend a lot of time in my unit tests writing the
&gt; structure:
&gt; 
&gt; public void testWhatever() {
&gt;    setup_stuff_here();
&gt;    more_setup_stuff_here();
&gt;    try {
&gt;       method_under_test();
&gt;    } catch(Exception e) {
&gt;       fail(e.getMessage());
&gt;    }
&gt; }

Ok, so if you _really_ need it:  include the JUnit-addons library and replace:

   fail(e.getMessage());

by

   junitx.framework.Assert.fail(e);

